markdown.t: The specFrame table lists details of individual specFrames present
in the survey.  A specFrame contains a set of spectra extracted from
a single twoDFrame.  Thus usually there is a 1:1 relation between
specFrames and twoDFrames.  However, it is possible for several
reasons (e.g. a 2d bias or other calibration frame), to have a twoDFrame for which there is no
corresponding specFrame.  A specFrame, however, must necessarily have
a corresponding twoDFrame from which it has been created. The distinction between
a specFrame and its source twoDFrame is that the latter is the spectrograph image
prior to spectral extraction (so may contain curved orders with spectra spread over
more than one column, and the pixel counts will be source plus sky) while a specFrame
is the result of pipeline spectral extraction run on the twoDFrame, and will contain
individual extracted spectra (or echelle orders) in the individual lines (think IRAF
multispec format).
Required constraints: primary key is (specFrameID)

specFrameID.name: specFrameID
specFrameID.description: SpecFrame identifier: unique identifier for each specFrame

fileName.name: fileName
fileName.description: The GES Science Archive filename at WFAU for the specFrame, eg. /path/filename.fits

gesField.name: gesField
gesField.description: GES name of the field observed (also name of enclosing directory)

nDispElems.name: nDispElems
nDispElems.description: Length of data axis 1 of the specFrame in the dispersion direction i.e. the number of wavelength elements

nSpectra.name: nSpectra
nSpectra.description: Length of data axis 2 of the specFrame in the spatial direction i.e. number of spectra/fibres

utDate.name: utDate
utDate.description: UT date when this file was written

grating.name: grating
grating.description: Grating central wavelength (as string to guarantee formatting)

object.name: object
object.description: Name of the frame (often the name of the guide star or a bright nearby object)

mjdObs.name: mjdObs
mjdObs.description: Modified Julian Date of the observation start

mjdEnd.name: mjdEnd
mjdEnd.description: Modified Julian Date of the observation end

archiveFileName.name: archiveFileName
archiveFileName.description: Archive File Name (ESO-SAF or CASU repository?)

argUsed.name: argUsed
argUsed.description: Flag indicating if ARGUS is used

plate.name: plate
plate.description: Identifier of the used positioner plate

deprecated.name: deprecated
deprecated.description: Deprecated flag: coded as current=0 or deprecated !=0

cuEventID.name: cuEventID
cuEventID.description: UID of curation event giving rise to this record

markdown.t: The Spectrum table lists details of individual spectra observed during
the survey.  Note that a given target star may (and often will) be
observed more than once during the survey, so a given targetID may have
several entries in the table; furthermore, early data releases may well
contain several pipeline processed versions of the same data for a given
target.
Required constraints: primary key is (specID)
(targetID) references Target(targetID)
(specFrameID) references SpecFrame(specFrameID)

specID.name: specID
specID.description: Spectrum identifier: unique identifier for each spectrum (4 MSB are the specFrameID; 4 LSB are the nSpec)

specFrameID.name: specFrameID
specFrameID.description: SpecFrame identifier of the SpecFrame from which the spectrum was extracted

targetID.name: targetID
targetID.description: Target identifer of the star being observed

fileName.name: fileName
fileName.description: The GES Science Archive filename at WFAU for the specFrame, eg. /path/filename.fits. Only for UVES SingleSpec files.

nSpecOld.name: nSpecOld
nSpecOld.description: The number of the spectrum before unused fibres were culled (equivalent to the number of the fibre)

cName.name: cName
cName.description: Object name formed from the coordinates of the object (can be used in place of object to give a unique name)

type.name: type
type.description: M for programme objects or S for sky fibres

spClass.name: spClass
spClass.description: The spectral class (STAR, SKY or LOWSN; the latter two classes do not have spectral fits done for them)

snr.name: snr
snr.description: The mean signal-to-noise ratio in the spectrum

skyOff.name: skyOff
skyOff.description: Offset to get the mean sky into coincidence with the current spectrum

skyScale.name: skyScale
skyScale.description: The scaling factor applied to the mean sky before subtracting from the current spectrum

rmsTrace.name: rmsTrace
rmsTrace.description: The RMS of the fit to the curvature of the spectrum on the detector

rmsArc.name: rmsArc
rmsArc.description: The RMS of the wavelength solution

ccfMax.description: The peak value of the cross correlation function

ccfWidth.name: ccfWidth
ccfWidth.description: Width of the peak of the cross correlation function

rvRedshift.description: The radial velocity measured from the cross correlation

skylineCor.name: skylineCor
skylineCor.description: The correction to be applied to correct for wavelength drift calculated from the sky lines in the observations

vacuumCor.name: vacuumCor

markdown.h: List of FITS keywords extracted from the headers of SpecFrames.

markdown.t: This table lists all the FITS keywords in all the SpecFrames ingested into
the archive.  It is not anticipated that these keywords will be accessed
often, since the most useful metadata keys are present as attributes in the
SpecFrame table. If, however, information from this table is required, note
that all data are stored as FITS key character strings so use of the built-in
SQL function CAST is required to perform operations within expressions on these
attributes.
Required constraints: primary key is (specFrameID, extNum, name)
(specFrameID) references SpecFrame(specFrameID)

specFrameID.name: specFrameID
specFrameID.description: specFrameID of the specFrame from which the keyword was extracted.

extNum.name: extNum
extNum.description: Extension number (0 corresponds to the primary HDU)

value.name: value
value.description: Value of the FITS keyword (copied as a character string)

units.name: units
units.description: Any units for the FITS keyword

markdown.h: Defines the group of spectra that make up an analysis in AstroAnalysis.

completeness.description: Flag, is the spectrum group complete: R - all files resolved ok; U one or more files undefined.

markdown.h: Combined results table for all GES spectral analysis.

markdown.t: This table contains the individual node and recommended astrophysical
parameters & abundances provided by the GES consortium for all stars
included in the survey.
It includes results provided by all the working groups and from both the
UVES and Giraffe spectrographs.
Notes:
All abundances of element X are given in the following format:
log ε(X) = log(N<sub>X</sub>/N<sub>H</sub>) + 12.0
Upper_Combined_X allowed flag values are:
0 = neutral detection;
1 = neutral upper limit;
2 = detection for combined results (neutral & ionised element);
3 = upper limit for combined results (neutral & ionised element)
Upper_X allowed flag values are:
0 = ionised detection
1 = ionised upper limit
Allowed values for limit flags on abundances derived from equivalent
widths and photometric temperatures:
0 = detection;
1 = upper limit
Required constraints: primary key is (specGroupID, wg, nodeID, isWgParams, uniqueness)
(targetID) references Target(targetID)
